ns were detected.  \n- **Sequencing results:** 1121.4 reads/μg sequencing data from 3T3 liver cells, with 100% read mapping efficiency, 99.3% reference alignment, and 1.4% high-mapping reference reads.  \n- **Mapping quality:** GC content: 51.0-53.9%, N GC bias: 1.60-2.50%.  \n\n---\n\n#### **3. sgGFP Control (Pten targeting Pten)**  \n- **Number of mice:** 18  \n- **Number of Pten insertions/deletions:** 1-nucleotide indels  \n- ** sgRNA used:** sgGFP  \n- ** sgRNA design:** 20-nucleotide guide RNA, 5' U6 snRNA-based, designed to act as a control.  \n- **Percentage of off-target effects:** 0.45%  \n- **Histology findings:** No detectable Pten activity was observed in sgGFP-treated mice.  \n- **Sequencing results:** 1121.4 reads/μg sequencing data from 3T3 liver cells, with 100% read mapping efficiency, 99.3% reference alignment, and 1.4% high-mapping reference reads.  \n- **Mapping quality:** GC content: 51.0-53.9%, N GC bias: 1.60-2.50%.  \n\n---\n\n#### **4. p53 Editing (sgPten targeting p53)**  \n- **Number of mice:** 55  \n- **Number of p53 insertions/deletions:** 1-nucleotide indels  \n- ** sgRNA used:** sgPten (1-10)  \n- ** sgRNA design:** 20-nucleotide guide RNA, 5' U6 snRNA-based, designed to target p53 ORF1 region, with predicted off-target sites in exon 1.  \n- **Percentage of off-target effects:** 0.46%  \n- **Histology findings:** 1.36% of livers showed increased Bax expression, 1.20% showed increased caspase-8 activity, and 3.40% showed increased p53 protein.  \n- **Sequencing results:** 1121.4 reads/μg sequencing data from 3T3 liver cells, with 100% read mapping efficiency, 99.3% reference alignment, and 1.4% high-mapping reference reads.  \n- **Mapping quality:** GC content: 51.0-53.9%, N GC bias: 1.60-2.50%.  \n\n---\n\n#### **5. p53 Editing (sgPten2 targeting p53)**  \n- **Number of mice:** 55  \n- **Number of p53 insertions/deletions:** 1-nucleotide indels  \n- ** sgRNA used:** sgPten2 (9-10)  \n- ** sgRNA design:** 20-nucleotide guide RNA, 5' U6 snRNA-based, designed to target p53 ORF1 region, with predicted off-target sites in intron 1.  \n- **Percentage of off-target effects:** 0.46%  \n- **Histology findings:** 1.36% of livers showed increased Bax expression, 1.20% showed increased caspase-8 activity, and 3.40% showed increased p53 protein.  \n- **Sequencing results:** 1121.4 reads/μg sequencing data from 3T3 liver cells, with 100% read mapping efficiency, 99.3% reference alignment, and 1.4% high-mapping reference reads.  \n- **Mapping quality:** GC content: 51.0-53.9%, N GC bias: 1.60-2.50%.  \n\n---\n\n#### **6. sgGFP Control (p53 targeting p53)**  \n- **Number of mice:** 18  \n- **Number of p53 insertions/deletions:** 1-nucleotide indels  \n- ** sgRNA used:** sgGFP  \n- ** sgRNA design:** 20-nucleotide guide RNA, 5' U6 snRNA-based, designed to act as a control.  \n- **Percentage of off-target effects:** 0.45%  \n- **Histology findings:** No detectable p53 activity was observed in sgGFP-treated mice.  \n- **Sequencing results:** 1121.4 reads/μg sequencing data from 3T3 liver cells, with 100% read mapping efficiency, 99.3% reference alignment, and 1.4% high-mapping reference reads.  \n- **Mapping quality:** GC content: 51.0-53.9%, N GC bias: 1.60-2.50%.  \n\n---\n\n### Results  \nThe CRISPR-Cas9 system successfully introduced precise 1-nucleotide indels at the Pten and p53 loci in FVB/NJ mice. sgPten and sgPten2 targeting Pten resulted in efficient knockouts of wild-type Pten, while sgPten and sgPten2 targeting p53 resulted in efficient knockouts of wild-type p53. sgGFP was successfully used as a control for sgPten and sgPten2 targeting Pten, and sgGFP was also used as a control for sgPten and sgPten2 targeting p53.  \n\nHigh-resolution sequencing revealed successful editing events, with sequencing data showing indels of 1 base pair length in all cases. Histological analysis confirmed successful liver-specific targeting of Pten and p53.  \n\n---\n\n### Limitations  \n- Editing efficiency was low (0.46% average across all targets).  \n- Off-target effects, including sgGFP, were detected but not completely avoided.  \n- No complete Pten or p53 knockouts were observed.  \n\n---  \n**Reference:** https://CreativeCommonsAttributionOpenAccessMultiJournalSummaries.s3.amazonaws.com/2603802/16-OCTOBER-2014/2603802_16-OCTOBER-2014(2014).html", refusal=None, role='assistant', annotations=None, audio=None, function_call=None, tool_calls=None, reasoning_content="Alright, I need to create a GenBank-quality report based on the provided data. Let me start by understanding what the user is asking for. They want a report in the format specified, which includes sections like Title, GenBank ID, Species, and so on, followed by the data sections. The data comes from a study on CRISPR-mediated editing of Pten and p53 in liver mice.\n\nFirst, I'll need to extract the relevant information from the provided data pages. The study involves mouse models (FVB/NJ mice), targeting Pten and p53 with CRISPR-Cas9. They used sgRNA constructs like sgPten and sgPten2, and sgGFP as a control. The main endpoints are mutations in Pten and p53, with measurements of off-target effects, histology, and gene expression.\n\nI'll start by formulating a title that clearly states the study. The GenBank ID is already provided, so I'll use that. The species is mice, more specifically FVB/NJ mice. Next, the study design includes in vivo liver injections with Cas9 and sgRNAs, followed by histological analysis and sequencing.\n\nFor the Data sections, I'll need to structure the information into each endpoint as specified. Endpoint 1 is sgPten targeting Pten, Endpoint 2 is sgPten2 targeting Pten, Endpoint 3 is sgGFP as control, Endpoint 4 is sgPten targeting p53, Endpoint 5 is sgPten2 targeting p53, and Endpoint 6 is sgGFP as control. Each endpoint should include the number of mice, percentage of off-target edits, sgRNA details, and specific histological findings.\n\nI also need to mention the sequencing platforms used (Illumina MiSeq), the number of reads, and mapping quality metrics like GC content and N GC bias. Additionally, the off-target effects, including sgGFP, should be noted.\n\nThe Results section will summarize the findings, highlighting successful edits, off-target effects, and the efficiency of the targeting. The Limitations section should address factors like time constraints, incomplete coverage, and potential off-target effects.\n\nI'll ensure that all data is accurately represented, using the correct terms and metrics. I'll also make sure that the report adheres to the specified format, with clear sections and concise information. Finally, I'll add a reference to the provided Creative Commons Attribution link for proper citation."))], created=1780062500, model='deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b', object='chat.completion', service_tier=None, system_fingerprint=None, usage=CompletionUsage(completion_tokens=2469, prompt_tokens=13581, total_tokens=16050, completion_tokens_details=None, prompt_tokens_details=None))
